## Section variant system

Every block exposes a Section Variant ACF field (Style tab, field name: section_variant). The selected value is output as a scoped CSS class on the block's outer wrapper only — never on inner wrappers.

Standard variant list (same across every block):
- default — base block styles, no override
- homepage-feature — elevated or hero-adjacent treatment on the homepage
- minimal — stripped-back, reduced padding or background
- split-feature — two-column or asymmetric layout treatment
- cards-feature — card-heavy section with grid emphasis
- inner-banner — compact banner treatment for interior pages

Rules:
- Variants describe design patterns, not pages. Never name a variant after a page (e.g. about-feature, work-banner).
- Only add a new variant when you have a genuinely new design pattern not covered by the six above.
- When a new variant is added, add it to every block's ACF JSON export so the dropdown stays consistent.

PHP pattern:
```php
$variant       = get_field('section_variant') ?: 'default';
$variant_class = 'block_prefix_variant_' . str_replace('-', '_', $variant);
// Outer wrapper only
<div class="block_outer_class <?= esc_attr($variant_class); ?>">
```

---

## Page-scoped block styling

WordPress outputs a page-{slug} class on the body tag automatically via body_class(). Use this to scope per-page block overrides without creating new variants or touching block CSS files.

Pattern:
```css
/* Base — applies everywhere */
.hero_variant_inner_banner .hero_block { min-height: 300px; }

/* Exception — one page only */
body.page-about .hero_variant_inner_banner .hero_block { min-height: 200px; }
```

Always write the base rule first, scoped exception below. Per-page overrides go in style.css Section 10 — never inside block CSS files.

If you are comma-separating many page slugs, the override should become the base rule and the exceptions should be the outliers.

